---
import GuideLayout from '../layouts/GuideLayout.astro';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'n8n vs Make (Integromat)?',
    answer: 'Make offers visual scenario building with operations pricing. n8n offers self-host and deeper dev extensibility.',
  },
];
---

<GuideLayout
  title="n8n vs Make — Comparison for Automators"
  description="Compare n8n vs Make (Integromat): operations pricing, self-hosting, AI workflows, and template libraries."
  path="/n8n-vs-make"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { name: 'Home', path: '/' },
    { name: 'n8n vs Make', path: '/n8n-vs-make' },
  ]}
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <p><strong>n8n vs Make</strong> pits two visual automation giants against each other.</p>

  <h2>Make strengths</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Polished UI for scenario design</li>
    <li>Large app connector library</li>
    <li>Good for marketing ops without code</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>n8n strengths</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Self-host and data control</li>
    <li>AI agent + MCP workflows</li>
    <li>Free templates at <a href="/workflows">n8n.gjam.in</a></li>
    <li>No per-operation tax when self-hosted</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Verdict</h2>
  <p>Make for marketing teams on SaaS only. n8n for product/engineering teams and AI-heavy stacks.</p>
</GuideLayout>
